00:00:45.248 --> 00:00:46.990
- Welcome to a Conversation with History,

00:00:46.990 --> 00:00:48.820
I'm Harry Kreisler of the Institute

00:00:48.820 --> 00:00:50.430
of International Studies.

00:00:50.430 --> 00:00:54.210
Our guest today is Alexandra Horowitz,

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:57.930
who is an Adjunct Associate
Professor of Psychology

00:00:57.930 --> 00:01:01.480
at Barnard College, Columbia University.

00:01:01.480 --> 00:01:04.190
She's the author of On Looking,

00:01:04.190 --> 00:01:06.930
Eleven Walks with Expert Eyes,

00:01:06.930 --> 00:01:11.930
and Inside of a Dog, What
Dogs See, Smell, and Know.

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:15.770
Alexandra, welcome to Berkeley.

00:01:15.770 --> 00:01:17.460
- Thanks, Harry.

00:01:17.460 --> 00:01:19.530
- Where were you born and raised?

00:01:19.530 --> 00:01:21.220
- I was born in Philadelphia,

00:01:21.220 --> 00:01:23.330
and I mostly grew up in Colorado.

00:01:23.330 --> 00:01:25.070
My father moved out to Colorado,

00:01:25.070 --> 00:01:28.720
and so I was a quasi-westerner early on.

00:01:28.720 --> 00:01:31.040
- And looking back, how did your parents

00:01:31.040 --> 00:01:33.103
influence your thinking about the world?

00:01:34.210 --> 00:01:35.150
- Oh a lot.

00:01:35.150 --> 00:01:38.410
Both my parents were trained as attorneys,

00:01:38.410 --> 00:01:40.620
my dad still practices.

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:44.550
And I think they have a
very analytical approach

00:01:44.550 --> 00:01:47.330
to problem solving, to thinking.

00:01:47.330 --> 00:01:50.500
That was instilled in me
from a pretty early age.

00:01:50.500 --> 00:01:52.370
- And what was the conversation like

00:01:52.370 --> 00:01:55.190
at the dinner table, about world events,

00:01:55.190 --> 00:01:57.260
about science, about what?

00:01:57.260 --> 00:01:58.250
Or about the law?

00:01:58.250 --> 00:02:00.410
- Well in some ways,
sometimes it was about the law

00:02:00.410 --> 00:02:02.450
actually, we talked about
the law a fair amount.

00:02:02.450 --> 00:02:03.560
And that was pretty intriguing,

00:02:03.560 --> 00:02:05.470
'cause there's the process
and I was interested

00:02:05.470 --> 00:02:07.070
in understanding the process,

00:02:07.070 --> 00:02:09.770
and seeing that you could
come to an end of a process.

00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:12.300
But also just about ordinary things.

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:13.160
What happened in the day,

00:02:13.160 --> 00:02:17.250
and really analyzing what
happened in our days,

00:02:17.250 --> 00:02:19.750
or social interaction, or,

00:02:19.750 --> 00:02:21.090
you know not just reporting

00:02:21.090 --> 00:02:24.150
but also kind of
ruminating on what it was.

00:02:24.150 --> 00:02:27.150
So we could have a long conversation about

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:29.530
a one little incident that happened

00:02:29.530 --> 00:02:31.170
at the grocery store, at school,

00:02:31.170 --> 00:02:33.470
or walking the dog.

00:02:33.470 --> 00:02:35.980
- And when did you acquire your first dog,

00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:37.750
if acquire is the right word?

00:02:37.750 --> 00:02:40.780
- I know, ownership is a
broad question. (laughs)

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:42.450
- So when--

00:02:42.450 --> 00:02:44.160
- At that time we were
all owners though, right?

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:45.090
- Yeah, yes, yeah.

00:02:45.090 --> 00:02:47.290
- And our family lived with dogs

00:02:47.290 --> 00:02:48.123
as long as I remember,

00:02:48.123 --> 00:02:50.400
I think from the time I was very young

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:51.480
we had a dog.

00:02:51.480 --> 00:02:55.800
My first dog I remember was
maybe a dog named Heidi,

00:02:55.800 --> 00:02:58.150
when I was six.

00:02:58.150 --> 00:03:00.350
And then I grew up with a dog,

00:03:00.350 --> 00:03:03.010
and even in college, I maybe
had a year or two in college

00:03:03.010 --> 00:03:04.550
where I didn't live with a dog,

00:03:04.550 --> 00:03:08.020
and then I had dogs in college.

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:09.580
So I actually have always lived with dogs.

00:03:09.580 --> 00:03:14.397
- When you were younger
and the family had a dog,

00:03:16.110 --> 00:03:18.410
did you find yourself observing them?

00:03:18.410 --> 00:03:22.390
Were you a scientist in
becoming at that point,

00:03:22.390 --> 00:03:24.440
or was it just the
friendship relationship?

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:27.140
- I don't think I, I don't remember being

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:31.630
scientific in my approach
to the dog at all.

00:03:31.630 --> 00:03:36.220
I think what I had was a
sensitivity to animals,

00:03:36.220 --> 00:03:41.220
and plants actually, I think
I was just kind of worried

00:03:41.790 --> 00:03:45.680
about their experience, or
what was happening with them.

00:03:45.680 --> 00:03:46.820
Not to say I couldn't forget,

00:03:46.820 --> 00:03:49.050
I wasn't that sensitive a kid.

00:03:49.050 --> 00:03:53.430
But I wasn't analyzing them.

00:03:53.430 --> 00:03:57.580
I just wanted to be assured
of their well being.

00:03:57.580 --> 00:04:00.860
And that I can remember
from a very early age.

00:04:00.860 --> 00:04:03.359
- Mm-hmm, and so when did,

00:04:03.359 --> 00:04:07.130
what were your first
steps towards science?

00:04:07.130 --> 00:04:08.930
Was that when you went to college?

00:04:08.930 --> 00:04:10.355
Or even before then?

00:04:10.355 --> 00:04:11.950
- I had interest in science,

00:04:11.950 --> 00:04:13.990
but not behavioral science exactly.

00:04:13.990 --> 00:04:15.694
You know, I was very
interested in physics.

00:04:15.694 --> 00:04:19.930
Again, I liked the iterative process

00:04:19.930 --> 00:04:21.770
that led to a result.

00:04:21.770 --> 00:04:23.670
So that's very satisfying in math

00:04:23.670 --> 00:04:26.440
and in science as a
secondary school student.

00:04:26.440 --> 00:04:29.530
In college I got very
interested in philosophy,

00:04:29.530 --> 00:04:32.733
and it actually diverted me
from science a little bit,

00:04:33.580 --> 00:04:36.960
but was ultimately I think
frustrating for that reason,

00:04:36.960 --> 00:04:40.490
wanting to come to a kind of end point,

00:04:40.490 --> 00:04:43.150
or at least periotic tentative end points

00:04:43.150 --> 00:04:45.550
that science allows you
to progress through.

00:04:45.550 --> 00:04:49.360
So it wasn't until after I earned my BA

00:04:49.360 --> 00:04:52.490
and I was working, and
away from academics,

00:04:52.490 --> 00:04:55.990
that I started thinking that
I'd like to know more about

00:04:55.990 --> 00:04:59.000
some of these topics that
I had just forgotten about.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:03.330
You know, in pursuing philosophy
in particular cognition,

00:05:03.330 --> 00:05:04.868
so that's when I started taking classes

00:05:04.868 --> 00:05:07.450
and I wound up applying to a PhD program.

00:05:07.450 --> 00:05:09.907
- Mm-hmm, and where did you do your PhD?

00:05:09.907 --> 00:05:12.470
- At University of California San Diego

00:05:12.470 --> 00:05:14.290
in the Cognitive Science Department.

00:05:14.290 --> 00:05:19.290
- And that, so you're a
cognitive psychologist,

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:23.167
but are you also a zoologist, or?

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:27.010
- Well you could almost say that.

00:05:27.010 --> 00:05:28.550
I mean in a way you get to be a little bit

00:05:28.550 --> 00:05:30.950
of a jack of all trades
as a cognitive scientist

00:05:30.950 --> 00:05:35.470
because the field itself was formed

00:05:35.470 --> 00:05:37.160
by philosophers, and psychologists,

00:05:37.160 --> 00:05:39.120
and neuroscientists, and anthropologists,

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:42.080
and computer scientists
who were all realizing

00:05:42.080 --> 00:05:43.940
that they were asking similar questions,

00:05:43.940 --> 00:05:45.500
just approaching it a different way.

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:49.281
Artificial intelligence wants
to know about the brain,

00:05:49.281 --> 00:05:51.510
and neuroscientists want to know

00:05:51.510 --> 00:05:55.718
whether the ideas of the brain
could be mapped, programmed,

00:05:55.718 --> 00:05:58.270
and then there are observers of behavior,

00:05:58.270 --> 00:06:00.320
and testers of behavior and so forth.

00:06:00.320 --> 00:06:05.320
So from that position,

00:06:06.439 --> 00:06:10.313
I could be called any one of
those things a little bit.

00:06:10.313 --> 00:06:12.030
I've never been called a neuroscientist

00:06:12.030 --> 00:06:13.640
or computer scientist but,

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:16.010
I started studying animal behavior

00:06:16.010 --> 00:06:18.440
and became a little bit
of what I would call

00:06:18.440 --> 00:06:20.690
a cognitive ethologist, right.

00:06:20.690 --> 00:06:24.060
Somebody who's looking at
animal behavior naturally,

00:06:24.060 --> 00:06:26.330
and observing, and then trying to make

00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:27.800
inferences about cognition.

00:06:27.800 --> 00:06:32.590
- Mm-hmm, and at San Diego were there any

00:06:32.590 --> 00:06:34.170
particular people that you worked with?

00:06:34.170 --> 00:06:35.850
Who did you do your dissertation on,

00:06:35.850 --> 00:06:40.850
and then how did you come
to this focus on dogs?

00:06:41.020 --> 00:06:43.430
- I came to the focus on dogs
a little bit accidentally,

00:06:43.430 --> 00:06:46.900
so I did start to get
interested in animal cognition,

00:06:46.900 --> 00:06:49.380
and what kind of inferences
we can make about

00:06:49.380 --> 00:06:50.950
non-human animal minds.

00:06:50.950 --> 00:06:54.320
And I was doing research with people who

00:06:54.320 --> 00:06:57.190
were studying the cognitive
behavior of animals,

00:06:57.190 --> 00:06:58.510
the bonobos for instance,

00:06:58.510 --> 00:07:01.956
or the social behavior of animals.

00:07:01.956 --> 00:07:05.720
I joined a rhinoceros
observation research project

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:09.063
at the Wild Animal Park
under Ron Swaysgood.

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:12.180
But then I got interested in dogs

00:07:12.180 --> 00:07:15.070
because I was interested
in the topic of play

00:07:15.070 --> 00:07:16.900
as a natural behavior,

00:07:16.900 --> 00:07:19.740
which is so interesting
in human development,

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:21.870
and what might let us see something

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:23.130
that allow us to make some inference

00:07:23.130 --> 00:07:25.230
about what the dogs understand or no.

00:07:25.230 --> 00:07:27.360
And so you'd look for a playing animal,

00:07:27.360 --> 00:07:29.610
and nobody I knew there
was studying an animal

00:07:29.610 --> 00:07:31.160
who was playing all the time.

00:07:31.160 --> 00:07:34.230
You know you could go
and watch the bonobos

00:07:34.230 --> 00:07:35.540
and they'd play once in a while,

00:07:35.540 --> 00:07:37.430
and then they'd go off in the private area

00:07:37.430 --> 00:07:39.150
of the enclosure and they'd play

00:07:39.150 --> 00:07:40.920
and you don't see them.

00:07:40.920 --> 00:07:44.240
But I realized I was watching
play three times a day.

00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:46.860
You know I had a dog and
I would watch him play.

00:07:46.860 --> 00:07:48.440
And so I got interested in studying dogs

00:07:48.440 --> 00:07:49.990
and there was no one studying dogs

00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:52.183
at UC San Diego, at least not in this way.

00:07:53.420 --> 00:07:57.970
But Mark Beckoff, who was
at UC Boulder in Colorado,

00:07:57.970 --> 00:08:00.287
had studied dogs as a
biologist for a long time.

00:08:00.287 --> 00:08:02.400
And I got in touch with him,

00:08:02.400 --> 00:08:05.160
and really learned distance from him

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:08.150
how to look at dog behavior,

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:10.170
and then at UC San Diego, Shirley Strum

00:08:10.170 --> 00:08:13.313
in the Anthropology Department,
who studies baboons,

00:08:14.760 --> 00:08:19.550
took me under her wing
to help me refine my

00:08:19.550 --> 00:08:21.490
ethology technique, and Jeff Elman,

00:08:21.490 --> 00:08:24.640
who was just somebody
who could do anything,

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:27.520
a kind of renaissance intellect

00:08:27.520 --> 00:08:29.610
in the Cognitive Science Department,

00:08:29.610 --> 00:08:31.040
took me on intellectually.

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:34.790
So I had these, a distant
mentor in Mark Beckoff,

00:08:34.790 --> 00:08:39.180
and Shirley Strum and Jeff
Elman were my committee chairs.

00:08:39.180 --> 00:08:40.700
- Well I can't help but ask you this.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:43.222
Do you think there was a bias against dogs

00:08:43.222 --> 00:08:47.380
in the sense that no one,
at least at San Diego,

00:08:47.380 --> 00:08:49.640
had taken in the sense that

00:08:49.640 --> 00:08:51.810
we sort of take them for granted?

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:53.235
- Oh yeah, oh for sure.

00:08:53.235 --> 00:08:55.390
There was a huge bias against dogs,

00:08:55.390 --> 00:08:57.710
and I shared that bias against dogs.

00:08:57.710 --> 00:09:00.910
When I thought about it,

00:09:00.910 --> 00:09:02.257
or somebody might have proposed to me,

00:09:02.257 --> 00:09:03.900
"Maybe you could study
dogs, they're playing."

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:05.960
And I really scoffed at the idea.

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:06.975
First of all, if you were interested

00:09:06.975 --> 00:09:08.920
in non-human animal minds

00:09:08.920 --> 00:09:11.320
you were gonna be looking
at a primate probably.

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:16.230
Because what, non-human
primates are gonna be

00:09:16.230 --> 00:09:19.260
the most connected to us.

00:09:19.260 --> 00:09:21.460
And so therefore the ones that have

00:09:21.460 --> 00:09:24.400
the interesting answers to
the questions you wanna ask.

00:09:24.400 --> 00:09:25.910
And dogs are so familiar.

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:29.160
I think, I've tried to think
back on why it could be

00:09:29.160 --> 00:09:31.970
that dogs were rejected
as a cognitive subject

00:09:31.970 --> 00:09:34.220
in 1996 or something,

00:09:34.220 --> 00:09:36.590
and I think it was just we already had

00:09:36.590 --> 00:09:38.680
this vocabulary to talk about dogs.

00:09:38.680 --> 00:09:40.100
And so no one was studying dogs.

00:09:40.100 --> 00:09:42.620
I remember a well-known
primatologist coming

00:09:42.620 --> 00:09:46.910
and visiting campus,
and I had just started

00:09:46.910 --> 00:09:48.850
to observe dogs, and I said,

00:09:48.850 --> 00:09:50.948
gee, I think there's really something,

00:09:50.948 --> 00:09:52.240
this might've been 1998.

00:09:52.240 --> 00:09:53.870
There's something really interesting here,

00:09:53.870 --> 00:09:55.770
and what do you think about this?

00:09:55.770 --> 00:09:58.450
And he really laughed at that idea.

00:09:58.450 --> 00:10:03.450
And now he and many
others are studying dogs.

00:10:03.560 --> 00:10:07.110
It's really exploded as an
interesting research topic.

00:10:07.110 --> 00:10:10.210
And I think a lot of
people had that realization

00:10:10.210 --> 00:10:12.343
right at the same time in
different parts of the world.

00:10:12.343 --> 00:10:14.500
There's a big group in
Hungary, for instance,

00:10:14.500 --> 00:10:15.333
that was studying dogs.

00:10:15.333 --> 00:10:18.690
- And is it the case that,

00:10:18.690 --> 00:10:22.480
I mean, I don't think your
research has gone there yet but

00:10:22.480 --> 00:10:25.420
that dogs in a way in
our closeness to dogs

00:10:25.420 --> 00:10:28.750
could tell us really something
about humans basically,

00:10:28.750 --> 00:10:32.010
in the sense that the
interaction between the two,

00:10:32.010 --> 00:10:32.913
dogs and humans.

00:10:33.970 --> 00:10:36.000
- Certainly, yeah, insofar as

00:10:37.824 --> 00:10:42.180
they are in many ways
reflecting the process

00:10:42.180 --> 00:10:45.947
of our ancestors for
some thousands of years.

00:10:45.947 --> 00:10:49.140
They reflect our selection of them, right?

00:10:49.140 --> 00:10:53.860
We might've chosen and decided to breed,

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:55.110
intentionally or not,

00:10:55.110 --> 00:10:57.860
those animals that had traits

00:10:57.860 --> 00:11:00.140
that were most familiar, or pleasing,

00:11:00.140 --> 00:11:01.870
or recognizable, you know,

00:11:01.870 --> 00:11:04.600
reflected us, mirrored us in some way.

00:11:04.600 --> 00:11:07.370
And so they're a demonstration of

00:11:07.370 --> 00:11:09.380
what we think is important in a companion

00:11:09.380 --> 00:11:10.213
in some ways,

00:11:10.213 --> 00:11:13.400
and I think that makes them
good companion animals,

00:11:13.400 --> 00:11:14.940
and such easy companion animals.

00:11:14.940 --> 00:11:18.350
So there is a lot of
interesting research, I think,

00:11:18.350 --> 00:11:20.060
which is comparative in that sense.

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:22.953
I'm more interested in a dog qua-dog,

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:27.352
but yeah, they reflect
back on us, certainly.

00:11:27.352 --> 00:11:29.320
- Have you ever thought of a comparison

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:31.300
between dogs and cats basically,

00:11:31.300 --> 00:11:34.810
in the sense that they're very different.

00:11:34.810 --> 00:11:36.300
- As domesticated creatures, right?

00:11:36.300 --> 00:11:38.680
- Yeah, as domesticated creatures, yeah.

00:11:38.680 --> 00:11:40.600
- Right, and the selection process

00:11:40.600 --> 00:11:42.943
must've been much different for cats.

00:11:43.960 --> 00:11:45.580
And that's because maybe you're starting

00:11:45.580 --> 00:11:48.360
with a really different species

00:11:48.360 --> 00:11:51.030
that doesn't have the
same kind of sociality

00:11:51.030 --> 00:11:53.920
and interactions in their groups

00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:58.483
as the proto-dog or
ancestor wolf did in theirs.

00:12:00.130 --> 00:12:03.764
But also they're much less
willing subjects, cats.

00:12:03.764 --> 00:12:04.760
(laughing)

00:12:04.760 --> 00:12:06.380
So that's probably limited.

00:12:06.380 --> 00:12:08.720
There's probably a bias
against cat cognition research

00:12:08.720 --> 00:12:10.540
because the cats you know,

00:12:10.540 --> 00:12:12.960
just won't walk into
the laboratory with you.

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:15.780
- So what did you wind up doing
your dissertation on then?

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:19.540
- I did it on the behaviors
of theory of mind,

00:12:19.540 --> 00:12:24.540
this meta-cognitive concept
that we apply to humans,

00:12:25.206 --> 00:12:28.010
and a kind of case study of dogs at play.

00:12:28.010 --> 00:12:33.010
So dyadic interactions between
dogs, rough and tumble play.

00:12:34.300 --> 00:12:36.820
So I was assessing that play behavior

00:12:36.820 --> 00:12:38.590
and seeing if there was
anything that looked like

00:12:38.590 --> 00:12:41.070
it was a precursor to or rudimentary

00:12:41.070 --> 00:12:44.920
understanding of other's minds.

00:12:44.920 --> 00:12:46.370
- Others being--

00:12:46.370 --> 00:12:47.203
- Dogs.

00:12:47.203 --> 00:12:48.904
- Dogs, yeah, other dogs.

00:12:48.904 --> 00:12:49.987
- Other dogs.

00:12:51.390 --> 00:12:55.260
- I like to ask my guests what they see

00:12:55.260 --> 00:12:59.640
as the skills involved in what you do,

00:12:59.640 --> 00:13:03.700
and how do you train to
acquire those skills?

00:13:03.700 --> 00:13:05.320
- I think for my research

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:08.433
it's mostly about
patience and observation.

00:13:09.640 --> 00:13:12.660
A lot of my research
has to do with watching.

00:13:12.660 --> 00:13:17.660
And somehow that's a
kind of attention skill

00:13:18.190 --> 00:13:22.520
that we don't develop that much

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:24.950
in normal schooling, I think.

00:13:24.950 --> 00:13:27.930
Not just seeing, but really observing.

00:13:27.930 --> 00:13:29.660
And one way that's easier to do that

00:13:29.660 --> 00:13:32.670
is observing through video playback.

00:13:32.670 --> 00:13:36.340
So you videotape a lot of
episodes of a behavior,

00:13:36.340 --> 00:13:37.900
and you watch it in slow motion,

00:13:37.900 --> 00:13:40.433
and you start seeing
something different happening.

00:13:41.330 --> 00:13:43.960
And so that's where
patience really comes in.

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:47.300
I mean watching dogs play is great fun,

00:13:47.300 --> 00:13:49.740
but the science of it only happens

00:13:49.740 --> 00:13:53.712
when you're watching a 30th
of a second of it at a time

00:13:53.712 --> 00:13:58.712
of that video playback,
which is extremely tedious

00:13:58.980 --> 00:14:01.583
in writing sequential behaviors down so,

00:14:03.050 --> 00:14:07.410
a 30 second playback might
take hours to code effectively.

00:14:07.410 --> 00:14:10.500
And so you have to be
interested in observation,

00:14:10.500 --> 00:14:14.693
and then you have to be very
patient to deconstruct it.

00:14:14.693 --> 00:14:15.840
- When you say code,

00:14:15.840 --> 00:14:18.110
explain to our audience
what you mean by that.

00:14:18.110 --> 00:14:22.950
- So any behavior, any
anthropologist or ethologist

00:14:22.950 --> 00:14:26.999
would be interested in finding out

00:14:26.999 --> 00:14:28.450
the parts of that behavior.

00:14:28.450 --> 00:14:30.340
We might say, an interview
is happening here

00:14:30.340 --> 00:14:33.410
but what constitutes that interview.

00:14:33.410 --> 00:14:36.810
And there are various levels
at which you could describe

00:14:36.810 --> 00:14:39.603
this behavior that's happening between us.

00:14:40.710 --> 00:14:42.290
And we choose some level,

00:14:42.290 --> 00:14:44.145
and we're not interested
in finger movements

00:14:44.145 --> 00:14:46.730
or limb extensions,

00:14:46.730 --> 00:14:49.590
but instead maybe we're
interested in the conversation.

00:14:49.590 --> 00:14:53.530
And a code would be
making a representation

00:14:53.530 --> 00:14:57.080
such that you could look
at lots of different

00:14:57.080 --> 00:14:59.540
instances of conversations
and if there are

00:14:59.540 --> 00:15:03.110
patterns that are similar
across those coded behaviors.

00:15:03.110 --> 00:15:05.870
- And in the case of a dog who

00:15:05.870 --> 00:15:08.830
when you come to the study of the dog,

00:15:08.830 --> 00:15:11.700
there isn't an enormous literature

00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:14.510
that this breakdown becomes,

00:15:14.510 --> 00:15:17.050
there's just an awful lot going on,

00:15:17.050 --> 00:15:18.520
that it's only through this kind of

00:15:18.520 --> 00:15:22.940
careful observation that you can see that.

00:15:22.940 --> 00:15:25.480
- Right, I think we see play for instance,

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:27.530
in dogs as a unitary behavior.

00:15:27.530 --> 00:15:29.400
It's just, they're playing,

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:31.430
then that's kind of the
end of the assessment

00:15:31.430 --> 00:15:32.700
of what's happening.

00:15:32.700 --> 00:15:35.760
But you could break it down
into smaller components,

00:15:35.760 --> 00:15:37.060
you could look at how they're using

00:15:37.060 --> 00:15:40.340
each other's attention
when they're communicating.

00:15:40.340 --> 00:15:42.130
You could look at dominance,
missive behaviors,

00:15:42.130 --> 00:15:43.610
lots of ways you could do it.

00:15:43.610 --> 00:15:46.390
And I used an ethogram,
a list of behaviors

00:15:46.390 --> 00:15:50.660
to code the behaviors I was looking at

00:15:50.660 --> 00:15:53.500
from Mark Beckoff and other people

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:55.860
who had studied dog behavior.

00:15:55.860 --> 00:15:58.570
And also from people who'd
studied other animal behaviors.

00:15:58.570 --> 00:16:02.360
So ethologists all use each
others ethograms to get ideas

00:16:02.360 --> 00:16:04.090
about what are the kinds of behaviors

00:16:04.090 --> 00:16:05.893
we might see in this animal.

00:16:06.970 --> 00:16:09.540
And now there are pretty exhaustive lists

00:16:09.540 --> 00:16:12.550
of ethograms of different
animal's behaviors.

00:16:12.550 --> 00:16:15.600
- So in a way it becomes like

00:16:15.600 --> 00:16:20.000
reading encrypted
conversations between humans.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.603
In other words, once you
break the encryption,

00:16:23.455 --> 00:16:26.060
there's a whole conversation going on,

00:16:26.060 --> 00:16:29.700
whether between dogs or
between dogs and humans.

00:16:29.700 --> 00:16:32.010
- Right, that make the
conversation work, right,

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:35.513
or that make the play work,
the constituent elements.

00:16:36.870 --> 00:16:40.060
Now your analogy only
breaks down insofar as

00:16:40.060 --> 00:16:41.580
that doesn't mean we suddenly understand

00:16:41.580 --> 00:16:42.867
it's meaning all the time,

00:16:42.867 --> 00:16:46.970
but we certainly have analyzed
it at a different level.

00:16:46.970 --> 00:16:49.400
And so we might have gained
another appreciation for

00:16:49.400 --> 00:16:54.400
for instance, how dogs
use turn taking in play,

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:57.300
even if we don't understand play.

00:16:57.300 --> 00:17:01.863
- And so you're really
exposing the complexity,

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:08.270
which might be an entry
point to other complexities

00:17:08.950 --> 00:17:11.860
in the relationship of dogs to each other.

00:17:11.860 --> 00:17:14.340
- Yeah, absolutely, I mean
I got interested in play

00:17:14.340 --> 00:17:19.340
because it's a context
in which it's possible.

00:17:19.800 --> 00:17:24.780
In humans we learn a lot
of understanding of others,

00:17:24.780 --> 00:17:28.810
so by playing with this
real, pretend distinction

00:17:28.810 --> 00:17:31.240
early in childhood, we
might start realizing oh,

00:17:31.240 --> 00:17:33.830
there's more than one way to view this

00:17:33.830 --> 00:17:35.360
banana I'm holding up to my ear.

00:17:35.360 --> 00:17:38.030
It's not just a banana,
but it's also a phone.

00:17:38.030 --> 00:17:41.210
And then oh, that person in front of me

00:17:41.210 --> 00:17:42.710
might not know the things I do,

00:17:42.710 --> 00:17:43.960
they know something else.

00:17:43.960 --> 00:17:45.480
That seems to be part of that development.

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:49.080
So one wonders if one looks
at play in other species

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:53.300
if they're also based on an understanding

00:17:53.300 --> 00:17:55.430
that the dogs would use in other context,

00:17:55.430 --> 00:17:58.590
which is of another animal's perspective.

00:17:58.590 --> 00:18:01.630
That they know, or believe,
or think different things

00:18:01.630 --> 00:18:04.180
than that dog believes.

00:18:04.180 --> 00:18:08.300
- What are their qualities of
temperament besides patient?

00:18:08.300 --> 00:18:11.430
It sounds like there's
a lot of empathy really.

00:18:11.430 --> 00:18:12.263
Is that--?

00:18:12.263 --> 00:18:15.900
- For me that definitely was a grounding

00:18:15.900 --> 00:18:18.640
for my interest in
looking at animals, right,

00:18:18.640 --> 00:18:20.390
and I think that's probably the case

00:18:20.390 --> 00:18:24.623
for a lot of other animal
behavior researchers.

00:18:26.030 --> 00:18:31.030
And a real sense of connection
with a non-human animal

00:18:33.910 --> 00:18:36.590
of any kind, and an interest,

00:18:36.590 --> 00:18:39.360
a curiosity about other animals.

00:18:39.360 --> 00:18:44.360
And desire to not just
have a simple answer

00:18:44.380 --> 00:18:45.860
as to what the animal is doing,

00:18:45.860 --> 00:18:46.860
what the animal is feeling,

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:49.600
but to really analyze their behavior

00:18:49.600 --> 00:18:51.890
before jumping to any conclusion.

00:18:51.890 --> 00:18:54.520
- Now what was your goal in writing

00:18:54.520 --> 00:18:56.640
The Inside of the Dog?

00:18:56.640 --> 00:19:01.640
Obviously in part it was
reporting on your research,

00:19:02.120 --> 00:19:06.000
but beyond that were there
other goals involved here?

00:19:06.000 --> 00:19:09.670
- You know I was then a dog researcher,

00:19:09.670 --> 00:19:11.800
I had gotten interested
in the dog as the dog,

00:19:11.800 --> 00:19:14.780
as opposed to just this
theory of mind entry

00:19:14.780 --> 00:19:17.220
into non-human animal minds.

00:19:17.220 --> 00:19:20.760
And I lived with dogs,
and one of my interests

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:24.270
was in that tension,
being a scientist of dogs

00:19:24.270 --> 00:19:28.910
and also an owner or liver with dogs.

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:32.070
And how we have two
different approaches to dogs.

00:19:32.070 --> 00:19:34.410
So I was wearing two
different hats all the time.

00:19:34.410 --> 00:19:37.440
You know the ways you deal
with the dog in your house,

00:19:37.440 --> 00:19:39.380
and the ways we looked
at dogs analytically,

00:19:39.380 --> 00:19:43.740
and an interest to bring
the latter to the former.

00:19:43.740 --> 00:19:46.430
Not just for me but for other owners,

00:19:46.430 --> 00:19:51.070
and saying, ah, these are
questions we form about our dogs.

00:19:51.070 --> 00:19:51.903
What do they know?

00:19:51.903 --> 00:19:52.736
What are they thinking?

00:19:52.736 --> 00:19:53.569
What do they understand?

00:19:53.569 --> 00:19:54.770
What do they think of me,

00:19:54.770 --> 00:19:55.817
people would always ask me,

00:19:55.817 --> 00:19:57.800
"What does my dog think of me?"

00:19:57.800 --> 00:19:59.930
And is there anything I
could bring from my approach

00:19:59.930 --> 00:20:04.860
or my results or the other dog
researchers results to date

00:20:04.860 --> 00:20:06.490
which would bear on those questions.

00:20:06.490 --> 00:20:10.360
So it's realizing that
there's a universe of people

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:12.670
who live with dogs who
have questions about them,

00:20:12.670 --> 00:20:15.310
and that now there's this science

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:18.073
that wasn't that well
reported on at that point,

00:20:19.580 --> 00:20:21.653
which would be fascinating to them.

00:20:22.643 --> 00:20:27.643
- What is, in your work, what
does creativity look like?

00:20:28.100 --> 00:20:32.520
I mean can you tell us
about an ah-ha moment

00:20:32.520 --> 00:20:36.130
where you suddenly came on something

00:20:36.130 --> 00:20:39.190
that was really surprising for you

00:20:39.190 --> 00:20:40.960
in the area of play?

00:20:40.960 --> 00:20:44.050
- Well it was, I guess I
have a couple possibilities

00:20:44.050 --> 00:20:45.440
that leap to my mind.

00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:48.210
One was even finding out
about the possibility of dogs

00:20:48.210 --> 00:20:50.440
as a cognitive subject,

00:20:50.440 --> 00:20:53.410
and that happened through
reading Mark Beckoff

00:20:53.410 --> 00:20:55.970
and Collin Allen's book, Species of Mind.

00:20:55.970 --> 00:20:58.470
And I distinctly remember Mark,

00:20:58.470 --> 00:21:01.873
who was studying the
behavior of dogs in play,

00:21:03.720 --> 00:21:07.074
made a suggestion that
maybe there's something

00:21:07.074 --> 00:21:10.400
about shared intentionality,

00:21:10.400 --> 00:21:11.830
understanding of intentionality

00:21:11.830 --> 00:21:14.070
in these play bows that
they do, the play signals,

00:21:14.070 --> 00:21:19.070
which seemed to be something
like a request for play,

00:21:19.300 --> 00:21:21.250
or an announcement that
I'm about to play with you,

00:21:21.250 --> 00:21:24.490
and perceive play, and
continue throughout play,

00:21:24.490 --> 00:21:26.240
and are very important for play.

00:21:26.240 --> 00:21:29.670
And so he just made the suggestion

00:21:29.670 --> 00:21:32.830
that there was something
meta-cognitive basically,

00:21:32.830 --> 00:21:35.820
about the dog's very simple act

00:21:35.820 --> 00:21:38.010
of going down on their front legs

00:21:38.010 --> 00:21:40.840
with the rump high in the
air, wagging their tail.

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:44.260
And that was, that moment
was really inspiring

00:21:44.260 --> 00:21:48.060
'cause I was very interested
in the meta-cognitive aspects,

00:21:48.060 --> 00:21:51.120
or possibilities in
non-human animal minds.

00:21:51.120 --> 00:21:52.880
You know, are they
thinking about thinking,

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:54.900
are they think about other's thinking?

00:21:54.900 --> 00:21:57.090
And here was somebody saying
a very simple behavior,

00:21:57.090 --> 00:21:58.590
if you looked at the context,

00:21:58.590 --> 00:22:00.010
might be connected to that.

00:22:00.010 --> 00:22:03.110
So I thought, whoa,
I've gotta look at that.

00:22:03.110 --> 00:22:05.220
And that's really what I then spent

00:22:05.220 --> 00:22:08.440
two years of research looking at.

00:22:08.440 --> 00:22:09.793
So that was a big moment.

00:22:10.860 --> 00:22:13.760
And I also think before I
started writing this book

00:22:13.760 --> 00:22:17.040
and I got interested in more of how

00:22:17.040 --> 00:22:20.630
the science could elucidate
the experience of the dog,

00:22:20.630 --> 00:22:24.450
I was reading other
biologists and came across

00:22:24.450 --> 00:22:27.860
Jakob von Uexkull who was influential

00:22:27.860 --> 00:22:32.860
in some areas of animal behavior research,

00:22:32.920 --> 00:22:36.559
but had kind of fallen out
of the popular literature,

00:22:36.559 --> 00:22:40.430
he wasn't really in favor
I guess, 20 years ago

00:22:41.380 --> 00:22:43.060
in animal behavior research.

00:22:43.060 --> 00:22:44.410
You didn't really hear his name a lot.

00:22:44.410 --> 00:22:47.493
But he had this idea,
the umwelt of the animal,

00:22:48.520 --> 00:22:50.810
that you could imagine the world view,

00:22:50.810 --> 00:22:55.810
the soap bubble in which
any animal existed,

00:22:56.420 --> 00:22:58.850
defined by the things that
are important or salient

00:22:58.850 --> 00:23:02.440
in their environment, in
their own sensory capacity,

00:23:02.440 --> 00:23:05.460
and that really tickled me.

00:23:05.460 --> 00:23:08.680
I realized he's telling me how to find out

00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:10.460
what the experience of the dog is,

00:23:10.460 --> 00:23:13.350
which is figure out what's
important in their environment

00:23:13.350 --> 00:23:14.810
from their point of view,

00:23:14.810 --> 00:23:16.700
watch their behavior to do that,

00:23:16.700 --> 00:23:19.070
and understand their senses,

00:23:19.070 --> 00:23:21.620
and therefore get a different picture

00:23:21.620 --> 00:23:24.800
of what they experience in
a space, and we can do that.

00:23:24.800 --> 00:23:27.180
And so that was a big moment too.

00:23:27.180 --> 00:23:29.790
And that's still very
influential in my thinking

00:23:29.790 --> 00:23:33.191
about how to research dog behavior.

00:23:33.191 --> 00:23:38.191
- In a way that sort of defines
the agenda for your book,

00:23:38.200 --> 00:23:40.580
and I wanna walk you through your book,

00:23:40.580 --> 00:23:45.580
and you really identify three broad areas

00:23:47.750 --> 00:23:49.420
that you wanna look at.

00:23:49.420 --> 00:23:50.520
State what those are,

00:23:50.520 --> 00:23:53.460
and then I'll walk you
through each of them.

00:23:53.460 --> 00:23:55.500
- The sensory areas?

00:23:55.500 --> 00:24:00.373
Well, olfaction, that's
a huge sensory area.

00:24:02.299 --> 00:24:03.870
There's a visual area,

00:24:03.870 --> 00:24:07.170
and who's gonna be in their visual space,

00:24:07.170 --> 00:24:09.453
and I'm not sure what the third area--

00:24:09.453 --> 00:24:11.480
- Well I guess what I
meant was the overall

00:24:11.480 --> 00:24:12.313
framework of the book,

00:24:12.313 --> 00:24:15.270
so it's looking at the dog's origins,

00:24:15.270 --> 00:24:17.120
it's sensibilities--
- then their senses.

00:24:17.120 --> 00:24:18.250
- Yeah, then their senses,

00:24:18.250 --> 00:24:20.100
and then their interactions with humans.

00:24:20.100 --> 00:24:22.790
- That's true, all right
so right, absolutely.

00:24:22.790 --> 00:24:24.360
- That's how I saw the book.

00:24:24.360 --> 00:24:25.193
- That's great.

00:24:25.193 --> 00:24:26.980
Well you know, everybody
reads it a different way.

00:24:26.980 --> 00:24:28.820
That is all in there.

00:24:28.820 --> 00:24:31.363
Right, so where does this dog come from,

00:24:32.610 --> 00:24:37.030
who is the dog, and then what
are their sensory capacities,

00:24:37.030 --> 00:24:41.703
perceptual experiences, and then humans,

00:24:42.580 --> 00:24:44.010
and what do they see of us,

00:24:44.010 --> 00:24:47.350
and how have we influenced their biology,

00:24:47.350 --> 00:24:49.800
and the interaction and bond.

00:24:49.800 --> 00:24:51.790
- So let's begin with the origins.

00:24:51.790 --> 00:24:56.010
They come, their origins
are in the family of wolves,

00:24:56.010 --> 00:24:57.820
I guess you could say,

00:24:57.820 --> 00:25:02.510
but we don't think about having a wolf

00:25:02.510 --> 00:25:03.943
in our house these days.

00:25:05.333 --> 00:25:07.670
- And I don't think there's
any atavistic possibility

00:25:07.670 --> 00:25:09.920
that the dog is going to
become the wolf again.

00:25:09.920 --> 00:25:12.120
- Right, right, maybe on television,

00:25:12.120 --> 00:25:14.620
but we'll leave that aside.

00:25:14.620 --> 00:25:18.810
But so what, talk a little about that,

00:25:18.810 --> 00:25:21.200
because as I read your book,

00:25:21.200 --> 00:25:23.480
what you're saying basically is

00:25:23.480 --> 00:25:27.550
it drew some positive things
from coming from that line.

00:25:27.550 --> 00:25:28.850
But on the other hand,

00:25:28.850 --> 00:25:31.860
there were major changes in its evolution.

00:25:31.860 --> 00:25:34.630
So what is it about a wolf

00:25:34.630 --> 00:25:39.630
that could be the
starting point for a dog?

00:25:41.070 --> 00:25:41.903
- Well I'll say first of all

00:25:41.903 --> 00:25:43.970
that I think the domestication story

00:25:43.970 --> 00:25:46.780
is still unfolding, right,

00:25:46.780 --> 00:25:49.070
there are still people who are trying to,

00:25:49.070 --> 00:25:53.800
and claim to find the earliest examples of

00:25:53.800 --> 00:25:58.440
the divergence between
the early canine ancestor

00:25:58.440 --> 00:26:00.710
kind of wolf and dogs.

00:26:00.710 --> 00:26:02.550
And it might've happened
in multiple places.

00:26:02.550 --> 00:26:04.980
But it looks like at some point,

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:07.940
one of the best theories is
really Ray Copenger's theory

00:26:07.940 --> 00:26:12.560
which is that dogs, or proto-dogs,

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:15.210
some wolves kind of self selected

00:26:16.100 --> 00:26:19.200
right about when humans were becoming

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:23.000
less nomadic and having settlements.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:26.720
And with any settlements
you kind of create

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:28.940
trash outside of your settlement.

00:26:28.940 --> 00:26:31.963
The food that goes
uneaten, the early dumps.

00:26:33.130 --> 00:26:37.453
And some wolves might have,
already a social species,

00:26:38.470 --> 00:26:43.240
felt less wary of this
animal in their environment,

00:26:43.240 --> 00:26:45.120
and approached this new food source,

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:47.280
a new ecological niche basically,

00:26:47.280 --> 00:26:51.170
that we created inadvertently,

00:26:51.170 --> 00:26:53.410
and therefore came into closer proximity

00:26:53.410 --> 00:26:54.720
with these early humans.

00:26:54.720 --> 00:26:59.580
And then might have started
to be taken in by us,

00:26:59.580 --> 00:27:03.600
and maybe because some of
them were appealing to us

00:27:03.600 --> 00:27:06.490
as puppies, maybe partly for
food, something like that,

00:27:06.490 --> 00:27:09.420
and then artificial
selection started after that.

00:27:09.420 --> 00:27:11.960
So this was a species,
and I wanna make clear,

00:27:11.960 --> 00:27:13.400
it wasn't today's wolf, right,

00:27:13.400 --> 00:27:14.940
it was some ancestor of today's wolf.

00:27:14.940 --> 00:27:17.820
So we look at the wolf today and we think,

